Latin America in the fight against the Coronavirus.
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unparalleled size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not face the crisis resolutely, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political reactions in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared public health protection to be their top priority.
Others, however, have unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders decided on populist and divisive politics in the midst of tragedy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of fatalities as low as possible.
The politicians must focus on improving the healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing vacant infrastructure like hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
In addition, Latin American countries must reject export controls on medical supplies and other essential resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) - in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump's reckless decision to freeze approximately $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need a stronger global collaboration of health authorities to boost testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – ultimately to bring the pandemic to an end.
The economic shock is enormous: not only was Latin America's domestic production disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the lack of tourism, fewer foreign remittances, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the collapse of demand.
Decisive measures are necessary to protect household incomes and prevent this scenario.
This means providing relief to the victims of the crisis, including informal and freelance workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Reliefs for companies are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and social security contributions protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a swift economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the wave of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system – and with it the entire national economy – is threatened.
Many companies, particularly small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the shortage of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferments, payment moratoriums, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This crisis demands not only unprecedented government-backed credit guarantees to ensure banks continue lending, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state-owned banks can play a leading role in this effort.
Overall, the measures will likely vary by country, but extraordinary budget resources will be needed everywhere to speed up the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without exacerbating the health risks.
The budget space in Latin America is even tighter today than it was after the 2008 global financial crisis.
Therefore, the budget burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
There is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, but this can be reduced by the governments' promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, especially for the smaller and less developed Latin American countries, urgent external support for household budgets and balance of payments is required.
Both private companies and states incurring higher deficits will likely also worsen the current accounts of the countries.
Recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the history of modern financial markets – have exacerbated the problem.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive a lot more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
He must take care of the short-term currency and budget needs of the countries and continue to support the economies in this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
To accomplish this, he needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a revamp of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, an non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the Fund's supervision.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity to meet the expected strong credit demand by immediately doubling the volume of the new credit agreements.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-barrier tools with fast disbursement, such as its instrument for rapid financing, or launch new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs cannot be approved in time.
Major central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can pass on liquidity to central banks.
In the domestic market, central banks must use all available instruments and, if necessary, create new ones to provide the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursements in the region and tap into high-liquidity global capital markets to be able to provide additional budget support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented by a debt write-off.
The multilateral development banks should also provide guidelines to countries on the various policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Timing is of the essence here.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unparalleled in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region can afford no delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-won civil liberties.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer to citizens.
